Medicare Charges Prediction Pipeline

We will be using the Hospital Charges for Inpatients dataset to determine if Deep Learning has an advantage at regression modeling. This is a dataset of 163K rows of hospital charge records from 3337 physicians.

Our goal is to use the data to predict the average Medicare charges for physicians. Note that the original dataset has been modified to use for regression. The "Average Total Payments" field had a 98% correlation with Medicare charges, as a result it was omitted.

Physician Level Regression, One Row Per Physician

In this example we will attempt to predict the summed average Medicare charge at a physician level. Each doctor will have a field for the 100 DRG codes. If a doctor does not have a charge then the value will be filled in with zero. We do this because for machine learning and RNNs the input has to be the same size for each row. With our second LSTM we will mask the zero values to see if we get better results in our prediction.

There are over 50 Provider States, creating dummy variables for each would cause the size of the dataset to explode. To keep these features in the dataset without increasing the number of columns we will use mean ordering where we replace the categorical value with the ranking based on the mean of the target variable. In theory this should lead to better results, but since we are using the training set only to perform the ordering it could possibly lead to overfitting.

Xtrain.shape

In [294]:
def order_categories(Xtrain, Xtest, ytrain, ytest, categories, target):
    dftrain = pd.concat([Xtrain, ytrain], axis=1).copy()
    dftest = pd.concat([Xtest, ytest], axis=1).copy()
    for col in categories:
        ordered_labels = dftrain.groupby(col).mean().sort_values(by=target).index
        ordinal_label = {k: i for i,k in enumerate(ordered_labels, 0)}
        dftrain[col] = dftrain[col].map(ordinal_label)
        dftest[col] = dftest[col].map(ordinal_label)
    dftrain.drop([target], axis=1, inplace= True)
    dftest.drop([target], axis=1, inplace=True)
    
    return dftrain, dftest

Step 2: Machine Learning Pipeline with GridSearch

We will use a Pipeline and GridSearch to find the best performing model through cross-validation. We will compare linear regression, ridge regression, random forests, Adaboost, XGBoost, and a multi-layer perceptron at multiple configurations for each. Once we have the best performing model we'll use the parameters for an output on the test set

In [21]:
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
In [22]:
from pipelinehelper import PipelineHelper
import random
random.seed(101)
Create regression pipeline
In [23]:
pipe = Pipeline([('regressor', PipelineHelper([('lr', LinearRegression()),
                                               ('rr', Ridge()),
                                              ('svm', svm.SVR()),
                                              ('rf', RandomForestRegressor()),
                                              ('ada', AdaBoostRegressor()),
                                              ('xgb', XGBRegressor()),
                                              ('mlpr', MLPRegressor()),
                                              ('lgbm', LGBMRegressor()),
                                              ('ebm', ExplainableBoostingRegressor(random_state=201, interactions=0))]))])

Results from Best Performer (Light Gradient Boosting)

Light GBM performed best on the training data, in fact variations of LGBM took the top 13 spots, Explainable Boosting with no grid came in 14th place, followed by two XGBoost variations.

Light Gradient Boosting (LightGBM) is purported to be an improvement on XGBoost. It reduces memory storage and is faster. It can also handle large scale data.

"It uses two novel techniques: Gradient-based One Side Sampling and Exclusive Feature Bundling (EFB) which fulfills the limitations of histogram-based algorithm that is primarily used in all GBDT (Gradient Boosting Decision Tree) frameworks. The two techniques of GOSS and EFB described below form the characteristics of LightGBM Algorithm. They comprise together to make the model work efficiently and provide it a cutting edge over other GBDT frameworks" https://www.geeksforgeeks.org/lightgbm-light-gradient-boosting-machine/

Essentially the boosting is done on a leaf level and features are binned together. It also bundles mutually exclusive features, from one round to the next it takes a sample of the worst performing examples (highest gradient/error) and trains an updated model based on these examples.

Can we best LightGBM with Deep Learning?

Step 4: Deep Learning in TensorFlow/Keras

In [136]:
from IPython.display import Image

We will utilize a sequential model in TensorFlow implemented in Keras. Keras is an API that takes the complexity out of TensorFlow. Keras is the default API sitting on top of TensorFlow 2 and this was the major improvement going from TensorFlow 1 to TensorFlow 2.

Artificial Neuron

The artificial neuron is based on the human brain. Each input (feature or prior layer) is multiplied by weights. These weights are summed and a bias is added. This is then summed up and an activation function is applied. The activation function is usually a non-linear function. The non-linear property allows neural networks to take the form of almost any function. This output then goes into another layer or the final output. Each layer can have different activation functions, the final output function can be configured to solve regression or classification problems.

In [138]:
Image(url='https://www.gabormelli.com/RKB/images/thumb/3/31/artificial-neuron-model.png/900px-artificial-neuron-model.png')
Out[138]:

Sequential Models

We will use a sequential model. This basically means that we are stacking model layers on top of each other and the input for the next layer is the output of the previous layer. For more complicated models we can use the functional option where we can enable branching and multiple inputs and outputs. Each blue dot is the same as the artificial neuron above. Typically layers are setup with neurons in increments of the powers of 2 (i.e. 32, 64, 128, etc.).

In [139]:
Image(url='https://editor.analyticsvidhya.com/uploads/48655toy%20network.png')
Out[139]:

Dense Layers

Dense layers are the basic building block of neural networks in TensorFlow. For each dense layer, you assign a given number of neurons. These layers are "fully connected", every input depends on every previous output. This is similar to regression, but the output can be non-linear, it is of the form sum of (a*x) + b (bias) for the number of input features and then for the output of the prior layer.

In [140]:
Image(url='https://th.bing.com/th/id/R.18a883b3ada38299d328eff2f0c56ad4?rik=Iyg92QtV5tcjIg&pid=ImgRaw&r=0')
Out[140]:

Activation Function (ReLu)

The Rectified Linear Activation Function (ReLu) is the activation function we will use for the internal weights. It is a non-linear function that of the form fx = max(0, x). Because it is so simple it is fast to implement. Earlier neural networks also suffered from a "vanishing gradient" problem where deeper networks were harder to train. The ReLu does not suffer from this problem as the gradient is not stuck between 0 and 1. Basically, each neuron in each layer is a math function. The input is a weight and a bias, this is multiplied against the features (in the first layer) or the output of the prior layer. Each variable is multiplied by the weight and then the bias is added. If the collective sum is greater than zero then the value flows through to the next layer. If it is less than zero then the value is zero, and essentially turns off, in which case no information from this neuron flows through to the next layer/output.

In [141]:
Image(url='https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-FXKBzl99Dsw/XcuH4nUoL2I/AAAAAAAAAjk/CCkhAAtSP0Qo1bDTCMFFMnmfqqRJie8qgCEwYBhgL/s1600/relu.png')
Out[141]:

The ReLu is the most common activation function, despite the limitation that neurons turn off if the ReLu is zero or less in practice performance does not seem to suffer

Regularization (L1L2/Elastic Net)

Deep learning can have several thousand, even millions of parameters, as a result models can overfit. To reduce training bias we will introduce L2 regularization. This is essentially the same regularization concept that we see in linear models. The weights are penalized for being too big, which should reduce bias in the model and lead to better generalization. L1L2 is a combination of ridge and lasso regularization techniques

Adam Optimization

Adaptive Movement Estimation (Adam) is a smart way of using decay, momentum and different step sizes to try to find the optimal solution for a problem. Adam is considered the "cutting edge" but in different situations one optimization type may outperform the other.

                    checkpoint_path = 'model_checkpoints_reg_dl' +  str(reg) + str(lr) + str(hid) + str(batch) +str(epo)
                    checkpoint = ModelCheckpoint(filepath=checkpoint_path,
                                                frequency='epoch',
                                                save_weights_only=True,
                                                save_best_only=True,
                                                monitor='loss',
                                                verbose=0)
                    tf.keras.backend.clear_session()
                    model = tf.keras.Sequential([
                        Dense(hidden_layers[hid], activation= 'relu', kernel_initializer='glorot_normal', bias_initializer=bias_initializer,kernel_regularizer=regularizer[reg],  input_shape=(input_shp,)),
                        Dense(hidden_layers[hid], activation= 'relu', kernel_initializer='glorot_normal', bias_initializer=bias_initializer,kernel_regularizer=regularizer[reg]),
                        Dense(hidden_layers[hid], activation= 'relu', kernel_initializer='glorot_normal', bias_initializer=bias_initializer,kernel_regularizer=regularizer[reg]),
                        Dense(hidden_layers[hid], activation= 'relu', kernel_initializer='glorot_normal', bias_initializer=bias_initializer,kernel_regularizer=regularizer[reg]),
                        Dense(1)
                    ])
                    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='mse', metrics=['mse', tfa.metrics.RSquare()])
                    model.fit(Xtrain, ytrain, epochs = epochs[epo], verbose=0, callbacks=[checkpoint])
                    model_num += 1
                    loss, mse, r2 = model.evaluate(Xtest, ytest)

                        r2_top = r2

                        ' batch size: ', batch_size[batch],\
                        ' optimizer: adam' \
                        ' epochs: ', epochs[epo]
                        print(optimal)

Recurrent Neural Networks (LSTM)

Recurrent neural networks (RNNs) are commonly used for natural language processing tasks such as machine translation and on time-series data such as stocks. Recurrent neural networks are different from feedforward networks in that they have a "feedback loop". The RNN keeps state by basically utilizing a moving average that includes data from the prior iterations.

The RNN that we will utilize is a long-short term RNN (LSTM). On sequential data this is believed to be beneficial for being able to "remember" long term sequences as well as short term sequences.

In [145]:
Image(url='https://cdn-images-1.medium.com/max/1600/1*Niu_c_FhGtLuHjrStkB_4Q.png')
Out[145]:

Sequential Predictions

With the feeback loop, RNNs have more flexibility than feedforward networks as they can make many to one or many to many predictions. We will use this advantage to try to make predictions on the aggregated sum as well as the individual Medicare charges. In theory the LSTM should be able to "remember" patterns in sequences and possibly lead to better predictions

Many to One LSTM

We will first test a many to one LSTM, complexity prevents us from creating a "grid" because the LSTM takes much longer to run than the feedforward network. The entire "sequence" of {Number of charges (1), Total Charge (1)}, {Number of charges (2), Total Charge (2)},.... {Number of charges (100), Total Charge (100)}... predict {Total Medicare Charge} will be used to predict the sum of the average Medicare charges

    ax.text(i, y[i], str(int(round(y[i],4)* 10000)/100) + '%', ha='center')

Conclusion

At the expense of a very large grid-search we were able to best all other models with a feedforward deep learning model. Considering that Explainable Boosting had no grid it performed extremely well. Light Gradient Boosting was the best perfomer with minimal tweaking. LSTM models perform poorly, in truth we juxtaposed a sequence with the DRG data, LSTMs are used in many cases in time series analyses, they may not perform well on CMS data without a time component compared to other models.
